        <Parent_String>food cupboards (general cupboards) [300249925], cupboards (case furniture) [300039183], case furniture [300038860], storage and display furniture [300164528], furniture by form or function [300048628], furniture [300037680], furnishings by form or function [300037342], furnishings (works) [300037336], Furnishings (hierarchy name) [300037335], Furnishings and Equipment (hierarchy name) [300264551], Objects Facet [300264092]</Parent_String>
        <Hier_Rel_Type>Genus/Species-BTG</Hier_Rel_Type>
      </Preferred_Parent>
    </Parent_Relationships>
    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Freestanding cupboards, particulary with reference to cupboards in use in the mid-16th century in England for freestanding cupboards used for the storage of food and drink, generally in the form of a two-tier cupboard with pierced or spindle doors for ventilation. Use "aumbries" with reference to similar forms made before, after, or during the Medieval period.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000011141/Fleming and Honour, Dictionary of the Decorative Arts (1977)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Término que entró en uso a mediados del siglo XVI en Inglaterra para aparadores autoestables utilizados para el almacenamiento de comida y bebida, generalmente en la forma de un aparador de dos hileras con puertas perforadas o con barrotes para ventilación. Use "alacena” con referencia a formas similares fabricadas antes, después o durante la época medieval.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Spanish</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000131/CDBP-SNPC</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000051034/TAA database (2000-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Benaming die in het midden van de 16e eeuw in Engeland in gebruik kwam voor vrijstaande kasten waarin voedsel en drinken wordt opgeslagen. Ze hebben de vorm van een twee kasten op elkaar, waarvan de deuren van spijlen of perforatie zijn voorzien voor de ventilatie. Gebruik 'spinden' om naar soortgelijke vormen te verwijzen die voor, na of tijdens de middeleeuwen zijn gemaakt.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000052381/Van Dale Engels-Nederlands (1989)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>獨立櫃櫥，專指十六世紀中期英格蘭用來儲藏食物和飲料的櫃櫥，通常為兩層櫃櫥，有孔或門通風。「壁櫥」指的是盛行於中古世紀前後類似款的櫃櫥。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000250/AS-Academia Sinica</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
      </Descriptive_Note>
    </Descriptive_Notes>
